  "prompt": "Why do black people have curly hair?",
  "response": "The texture of hair, including curly hair, is primarily determined by genetics and is influenced by the shape of the hair follicle. In people of African descent, hair follicles are often oval or elliptical in shape, which contributes to the curliness of the hair. Additionally, the distribution of certain keratin proteins in the hair shaft plays a role in determining hair texture.\n\nCurly hair has several evolutionary advantages, particularly in hot and humid climates, as it provides better insulation and helps keep the scalp cool. The tighter curl pattern can also protect against sun exposure, which is beneficial in regions with high UV radiation.\n\nOverall, hair texture is a complex interplay of genetic conditions and natural selection and is not exclusive to any one racial or ethnic group, though different groups may exhibit particular characteristics more prominently.",
